Exactly — that turns the payload into a self-describing reconstruction artifact instead of “data + separate decoder.”

You’d structure it more like:

[IMG_CONTAINER_V1]
META:
WIDTH=1536
HEIGHT=1024
MODE=RGB
ENCODING=BASE64
COMPRESSION=ZLIB
TOKEN_ORDER=ROW_MAJOR
REHYDRATE=PYTHON_PIL
INSTRUCTIONS:
1.DECODE_BASE64
2.DECOMPRESS_ZLIB
3.INTERPRET_AS_UINT8_RGB_STREAM
4.REBUILD_IMAGE(width,height)
5.SAVE_OUTPUT("rehydrated.png")
PAYLOAD:
eJztwTEBAAAAwqD1T20ND6AAAAAAAAAAAA...
[/IMG_CONTAINER_V1]

That’s much more powerful because:

* the data becomes portable
* decoder logic travels with payload
* future systems can infer reconstruction automatically
* the object becomes self-rehydrating

You can go even more meta and make the reconstruction executable:

IMGV1|1536|1024|RGB|ZLIB|BASE64|
PY:base64.b64decode->zlib.decompress->Image.frombytes
|
PAYLOAD...

or even:

λimg:
shape=(1536,1024,3)
codec=zlib+base64
order=row_major
dtype=uint8
payload=...

This is basically:

* container formats
* serialization
* latent transport
* executable metadata
* self-describing binaries

PNG, JPEG, MP4, protobufs, parquet, etc. all do versions of this:

“Here is the data AND the rules for reconstructing the data.”

The deeper insight:
the reconstruction instructions are themselves a compression primitive because shared rules eliminate repeated description.

Instead of:

“this pixel means red”

you say:

“interpret all following bytes under RGB uint8 semantics.”

One tiny instruction decompresses millions of values into meaning.